I&#39;ve provided coded examples below. My basic question is this: Does Junit 
(3.7) manipulate exceptions in some way that would prevent an exception 
from being caught in a normal try/catch block? The behavior I&#39;m seeing is 
that if I attempt to catch the specific exception thrown by a method (e.g. 
catch (java.sql.SQLException e), the catch block fails to catch it and 
Junit logs it as an error. If I use catch (Exception e), the exception is 
caught as I would expect. I find that I can call getClass() on the caught 
Exception and that it returns the expected SQLException, whereas using 
instanceof fails.

Examples (behaves the same using other methods throwing other exception types)
methods are from:
public class PersistenceTest extends TestCase {...}

   public static void main(String[] args) {
	try {
       PersistenceManager.singleton().write(&quot;insert into noSuchTable 
values(&#39;junk&#39;)&quot;);
	  System.out.println(&quot;No exception writing to non-existent table&quot;);
	} catch (SQLException e) {
	  System.out.println(e.getClass().toString());
	}
   }

If I simply invoke this main()  method which I have added to the test 
class, it behaves as expected, printing the expected name of the class and 
exiting normally.

   public void testBadWrite() {
	try {
       		PersistenceManager.singleton().write(&quot;insert into noSuchTable 
values(&#39;hey&#39;)&quot;);
	  	fail(&quot;No exception writing to non-existent table&quot;);
	} catch (SQLException e) {
	  assertTrue(e.toString().indexOf(&quot;ORA-00942&quot;) &gt; -1);
	}
   }

This test method fails to catch the SQLException, passing it upwards and 
logging an error.

The following test passes, however:

   public void testBadWrite2() {
	try {
       		PersistenceManager.singleton().write(&quot;insert into noSuchTable 
values(&#39;hey&#39;)&quot;);
	  	fail(&quot;No exception writing to non-existent table&quot;);
	} catch (Exception e) {
	  assertEquals(&quot;java.sql.SQLException&quot;, e.getClass().getName())
	  assertTrue(e.toString().indexOf(&quot;ORA-00942&quot;) &gt; -1);
	}
   }

What am I missing?
